2) How that preference guides the decision: Given the sole, explicit preference is a fondness for listening to CDs, it is reasonable to favor the candidate that best leverages the strengths of the CD format — namely a cohesive, engaging album experience with production and dynamics that reward focused listening from start to finish. Album-Oriented Rock (AOR) and classic rock albums are specifically produced with an emphasis on sequencing, full-album flow, and instrumental dynamics, which tend to make for a more immersive CD listening session. By contrast, a "Greatest Hits" compilation in pop/bubblegum/oldies format is typically a collection of individually catchy singles optimized for casual or radio-style listening rather than a single, continuous album experience.
3) Specific, fact-based reasons for choosing High Voltage and rejecting The Monkees – Greatest Hits:
- Album orientation: High Voltage is categorized as Classic Rock / Album-Oriented Rock (AOR). AOR by definition emphasizes the album as a listening unit — production choices, sequencing, and instrumental arrangements are intended to be appreciated across the whole record. That aligns directly with the explicit enjoyment of listening to CDs as a medium for immersive, start-to-finish listening.
- Listening dynamics and replay value: Classic rock/AOR albums usually feature dynamic arrangements, guitar- and rhythm-driven performances, and production qualities that benefit from the higher-fidelity, uninterrupted-playback nature of a CD. Those qualities produce a richer, more engaging long-form listening session for someone who values CD listening.
- Cohesion versus single-driven compilation: The Monkees - Greatest Hits is a pop/oldies/bubblegum compilation of individual hit singles. While those tracks are widely popular and immediately enjoyable, they are oriented toward standalone playback and nostalgia rather than a unified album journey. For a listener whose declared preference is to savor CDs as albums, a greatest-hits compilation is less well matched.
- Audience fit: Because my only stated preference concerns enjoying CDs themselves (not just individual hit songs), I prioritize the album that offers a structured, album-level listening experience. High Voltage fits that priority better than a hit-collection of short, radio-friendly singles.
In summary, since the only explicit preference is a love of listening to CDs, I selected High Voltage because its AOR/classic-rock characteristics make it better suited to the immersive, album-focused listening experience that a CD enthusiast is likely to value. The Monkees Greatest Hits is a strong, popular collection of singles, but it is more oriented toward casual, track-by-track listening and therefore less aligned with the specific CD-centered preference I do have.

